subSubSection.paragraph:
Description
. 
Male
(
Holotype
). Total length 1.1. Carapace length 0.5, ovoid; narrowing gradually anteriorly; yellow, flat pars cephalic, fovea absent (
Fig. 7A
). Clypeus length 0.02, with a pair of long bristles (
Fig. 8A
). Eyes: PME oval; ALE and PLE rounded, ranging from opalescent or white (

Fig. 8A 
–
B

). Chelicerae light yellow; promargin with six teeth, attached to a very long lamina (
Fig. 8C
); retromargin without two very small teeth. Sternum yellow. Endites yellow, with large serrula with more than 15 denticles, distal macrosetae paired and crosier-like, and many multifid macrosetae present (
Fig. 8D
). Labium yellow, sulcated distally (
Fig. 8D
). Legs cream; formula 4123; total length: I 1.8; II 1.6; III 1.4; IV 2.0. Male palp: palpal femur length 0.02; palpal tibia enlarged basally; cymbium conical distally, bearing subdistal pair of modified setae and a projected and bifid tarsal organ (
Fig. 8F
); bulb spherical (

Figs 7B 
–
D

; 
9A
); conductor longer than SCI, enlarged at base (

Figs 9A 
–
C

); embolus with small and conical SCII, very short SCIII and voluminous SCIV (

Figs 7E 
–
F

; 

9A 
–
F

). Abdomen length 0.6, oval; uniformly gray. Three epiandrous spigots, with large, conic and striated base (
Fig. 8E
). Colulus triangular with six bristles.

Female ( Paratype , IBSP 207354). Total length: 1.05; carapace length: 0.45; Carapace as in male, light yellow pattern ( Fig. 10A ). Pedipalp without claw, with conical tip and subdistal bifid tarsal organ ( Fig. 11D ). Clypeus: 0.02 diameter, with setae as in male. Eyes, chelicerae, sternum, endites and labium (
Fig. 11A – C
) as in male. Legs as in male; formula 4123, total length: I 1.6; II 1.5; III 1.2; IV 1.8. Abdomen length 0.5, yellow ( Fig. 10A ). Colulus triangular with six bristles. Genitalia externally with long and distally curved lateral plates, large ventral plate and terminal depression sulcated (
Figs 10B – D
;
11E – F
); internally with together and paired spermathecae, and afferent spermathecae curved distally (
Fig. 10E – F
).
